Holoprosencephaly (HPE) is considered the leading abnormality of the brain and 
face in humans and is frequently associated with a wide spectrum of specific 
craniofacial anomalies including mid-line facial clefts, cyclopia and nasal 
irregularities. A standard course of treatment has not been developed and 
management is symptomatic and supportive. In this work, the authors discuss the 
wide-ranging spectrum of HPE and propose surgical guidelines to provide more 
uniform and appropriate care to patients suffering from holoprosencephaly. 
Assessment of the patient's brain abnormality is essential in determining the 
extent and benefit of surgical intervention. The authors discuss a median 
straight-line repair of the lip and repair of the anterior palate in a one-year 
old female and review the risks and benefits of surgery. Consistent with the 
ethical approach of surgical beneficence, the authors recommend intervention at 
the earliest possible time.

